● Why createStarRating is a separate function:

  The star widget has its own internal state (updateStars) and its own
  DOM-building loop. Inlining all of that inside createMovieCard would make it
  hard to read. Extracting it keeps each function doing one thing.

  Why card.appendChild instead of putting stars in innerHTML:

  innerHTML is string-based — you can't attach event listeners to elements that
  don't exist yet. Building the stars as real DOM nodes first and appending them
   lets each <button> get its own click listener with i correctly closed over.

  Why updateStars is defined inside createStarRating:

  It closes over container, so it can always find the right stars regardless of
  how many cards are on the page. No ID-based lookups needed.

  CSS hooks you get for free:

  .star { cursor: pointer; font-size: 1.2rem; }
  .star.filled { opacity: 1; }
  .star:not(.filled) { opacity: 0.4; }

