● What changed and why:

  Restructured HTML — the old markup used <p> tags with inline text and a <span>
   for the number, which made it impossible to style icon, value, and label as
  distinct layers. Each stat now has its own <div class="stat-card"> with three
  clearly separated children: icon, value, label.

  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr) — three equal columns that stay
  side-by-side on desktop. This is more intentional than auto-fill here since
  the number of stats is fixed; you want them to always appear as a row.

  Icon on top, big number in the middle, small label below — this vertical stack
   is the standard "metric card" pattern (used by dashboards everywhere) because
   the eye lands on the number first, then the label confirms what it means. The
   icon adds personality and makes each card scannable before reading text.

  font-size: 1.8rem / font-weight: 800 on .stat-value — the number should be the
   loudest element on the card. The large size with letter-spacing: -1px gives
  it a compact, data-display feel.

  .stats-heading separated from #stats — the heading is styled as a small
  section label (uppercase, letter-spacing) that sits above the grid rather than
   inside a flex container. This keeps the section header visually distinct from
   the cards themselves.

  Responsive: stacks to 1fr on mobile — three narrow columns on a small phone
  would make the cards too cramped. Single column reads cleanly at any width.

